es.  Look at fun like<br />&gt; arch/x86/pci/sta2x11-fixup.c for how ugly these mappings could look.<br />&gt;<br />&gt; It also means that we might have setup swiotlb on just about every<br />&gt; 32-bit architecture, even if it has no real addressing limit except for<br />&gt; the one we imposed.<br /><br />No. Really. If there's no iotlb, then you just mark that one page<br />reserved. It simply doesn't get used. It doesn't mean you suddenly<br />need a swiotlb.<br /><br />If there *is* a iotlb, none of this should matter, because you'd just<br />never map anything into that page.<br /><br />But whatever. It's independent from the patch series under discussion.<br />Make dma_mapping_error() at least return a real error (eg -EINVAL, or<br />whatever is the common error), and we can maybe do this later.<br /><br />Or, better yet, plan on removing the single-page dma mappign entirely<br />at a later date, and make the issue moot.<br /><br />              Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
